Here's how to implement all three:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button (in `EditProductPage.xaml`)

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with back command and dirty tracking

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    public ICommand BackCommand => new AsyncRelayCommand(OnBackAsync);

    async Task OnBackAsync()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return; // cancel navigation
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/swipe back in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom `BackCommand` handles the button, but users can also swipe back or press the hardware back key. Guard that in `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage?.BindingContext
            is EditProductViewModel { HasUnsavedChanges: true })
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `TextOverride="Cancel"` replaces the back arrow with "Cancel" text.
- `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks in `OnNavigating` â€” without it, navigation completes before the dialog resolves.
- The `OnNavigating` guard catches hardware/gesture back; the `BackCommand` handles the button tap. To avoid a double-prompt, set `HasUnsavedChanges = false` before calling `GoToAsync("..")` in the command, or use a flag to skip the guard when the command triggers the pop.
